## Seeing Everything

If you create a variable right in the main body of your JavaScript file (not inside any `{}`), it has **Global Scope**.

Global variables are like the sun ☀️. Everything on the planet (every function and block in the file) can see and use them.

```javascript
let userName = "Alice"; // Global Scope

function sayHi() {
  // Functions can perfectly see global variables!
  console.log("Hi, " + userName);
}
sayHi();
```

## Keeping Secrets

If you create a variable *inside* a set of curly braces `{}` — like inside a function, an if-statement, or a loop — it is **Local Scope** (or Block Scope).

It is trapped! It only exists while that block is running, and nothing outside the block can see it.

```javascript
function createPassword() {
  let secretCode = "1234"; // Local Scope
}

createPassword();

// Error! secretCode does not exist out here!
console.log(secretCode); 
```

